<font color="#FF0000">VA STUFF</font><br>
<tt>Fri Sep 26  5:56:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To set the record straight, the VA uses the Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory (MMPI), the Mississippi Scale for Combat-Related PTSD, the Beck Depression Inventory, and a few other smaller tests in their diagnosis of PTSD. In addition, the Psychiatrists and Clinical Psychologists probe your mind over the course of a few months of sessions. The tests may be administered more than once. There are a few other queasy things they can do, like deliberately trigger you, but these are not in the normal course of things. It is the overall information base that determines the diagnosis.<br><br>
The medical side is one thing.<br><br>
The rest of it is like being refused admission to the hospital because the receptionist does not clearly see objective evidence of the heart attack you are experiencing on the front steps.<br><br>
The Admin side is clearly another thing, from another planet not in this solar system. <br><br>
So, even if their diagnosis is uncontrovertable, and the treatment they administer is intensive and agressive, and outside independent professionals agree, the rest of the VA process can leave you triggered all over the place, insulted, and denegrated.  <br><br>
A very strange situation, indeed. If there is a problem anywhere, it is the irrational bipolar organizational illness the VA manifests in their witch trial assessment of your veracity.    
